data.content:
## What breaks

In EF Core 9, the Cosmos DB provider **removed native sync support** and began throwing `InvalidOperationException` for synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`, etc.). A temporary opt-in re-enabled sync-over-async behavior:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(connectionString, database, cosmos =>
    cosmos.AllowSynchronousQueryExecution());
```

In **.NET 11 / EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous query/save call on the Cosmos provider throws `InvalidOperationException` — no workaround.

## What to do

Convert all sync calls to their `async` counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's a local tracking operation, not a DB call)
- Callers must `await` — this ripples up the call chain (`async` all the way)

This is Cosmos-specific; the relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync APIs.
